WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.800
 So you just finished some in-depth work on a 6502 CPU emulator.

00:00:06.800 --> 00:00:12.560
 Now you might think that the only reason we ever use CPU emulators are for learning.

00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:18.080
 And they're great for learning, right? So I can give you a screen, and it has a program counter,

00:00:18.080 --> 00:00:22.800
 and a Z flag, and an N flag, and instruction memory, and you can go change the instruction memory,

00:00:22.800 --> 00:00:26.240
 you can start it, you can stop it, it prints a lot of stuff out.

00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:29.520
 You can hover over an instruction, and it shows you what the instruction is,

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:34.000
 and what the ASCII character might be stored there, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:37.200
 It keeps it really simple, so we can write pretty small programs.

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:40.960
 We can also look at the emulator code itself, and I've got in the upper corner a

00:00:40.960 --> 00:00:48.320
 URL that is the actual machine code emulator that's running when you're doing your assignments,

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:52.160
 or just playing with it. So if you go look at that, it's JavaScript,

00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:55.200
 and you've learned JavaScript, and it has to run in the browser.

00:00:55.200 --> 00:01:02.640
 So I have implemented a 6502 instruction set in JavaScript in a browser.

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:06.720
 The core of this is a function called execute_step, which should be called like

00:01:06.720 --> 00:01:11.440
 fetch_execute_cycle, because what it really does is it's going to run one instruction.

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:15.440
 So which instruction is it going to run? Well, you can see in that first line,

00:01:15.440 --> 00:01:19.040
 it's going to look at this.cpu.pc, the program counter.

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:21.520
 Where are the instructions? Well, they're in an array.

00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:24.880
 So we're going to use the PC to look up the instruction in the array.

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:29.040
 What's the instruction? It's an integer from 0 through 255.

00:01:29.040 --> 00:01:32.880
 It's a single 8-bit number. And so the next thing it's going to do is

00:01:32.880 --> 00:01:38.240
 have a big long if-then-else with like 40 or 50 different instructions.

00:01:38.240 --> 00:01:41.440
 The first instruction it checks to see is if we got all zeros.

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:46.160
 Well, the 000 instruction is the break, the halt.

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:52.080
 And so what happens is the emulator prints the output from the data memory,

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:57.040
 and then it sets itself to not running, and then the fetch_execute_cycle stops.

00:01:57.040 --> 00:02:00.080
 And there's a bunch more else, else, else, else.

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:04.000
 If it doesn't find an instruction that it understands, it has one last else

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:07.040
 that blows up and sets it to running equals false.

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:11.200
 You might just go have some fun and see if you can figure out a bit pattern

00:02:11.200 --> 00:02:16.000
 that will cause the emulator to blow up with an unknown instruction.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.160
 And after we've processed one instruction, well, we advance the program counter.

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:22.960
 It's what we do with the fetch_execute_cycle.

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:26.640
 Now, if there was a jump, if one of those instructions was jump instruction,

00:02:26.640 --> 00:02:30.080
 it already changed the PC. Do you remember how I told you that

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:33.120
 a jump instruction is kind of like a load into the PC?

00:02:33.120 --> 00:02:35.760
 It's almost like a load immediate into the PC.

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:40.960
 So that code up in the instruction processing sets the PC increment to 0

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:46.880
 to indicate that it's already been changed to a completely new location by a jump.

00:02:46.880 --> 00:02:53.760
 So if the PC increment is greater than 0, we simply say add the PC increment.

00:02:53.760 --> 00:02:57.680
 That little mask is there to make sure it doesn't get bigger than 256

00:02:57.680 --> 00:03:01.120
 because there's only 256 instructions in the instruction memory.

00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:06.000
 And the PC increment is going to either be 1 if it's an 8-bit instruction

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:09.680
 or 2 if it's a 16-bit instruction.

00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:14.320
 Digging a little more deeply into some of those else-if, else-if, else-if, else-ifs,

00:03:14.320 --> 00:03:17.920
 you can see the load accumulator immediate instruction.

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:19.920
 It's a 0x89.

00:03:19.920 --> 00:03:23.760
 And what we do is we say, oh, let's get that immediate value.

00:03:23.760 --> 00:03:28.800
 Take that CPU instructions and go 1 beyond the PC and grab it.

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:30.880
 So that's the number that we're loading.

00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:32.160
 And what do we do?

00:03:32.160 --> 00:03:35.120
 Well, we take the immediate value and we put it in the accumulator.

00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:38.240
 And every time you change the accumulator, you've got to update the Z and the N flags.

00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:39.920
 So we've got a function to do that.

00:03:39.920 --> 00:03:42.160
 And then we say, hey, this was a 16-bit instruction.

00:03:42.960 --> 00:03:44.480
 Increment the PC by 2.

00:03:44.480 --> 00:03:46.400
 Subtract immediate.

00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:51.680
 Again, we grab the immediate, which is the immediately following after the program counter.

00:03:51.680 --> 00:03:52.800
 We compute the difference.

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:57.440
 And then we set the accumulator to be the difference.

00:03:57.440 --> 00:04:02.960
 Update the status flags because we changed the accumulator and set the PC increment to 2.

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:04.720
 And we do like something a little more complex,

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:09.360
 which is a load with an address and an offset by the X register.

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:13.200
 Again, the base address is an immediate.

00:04:13.200 --> 00:04:17.120
 So we go 1 beyond the program counter and grab that.

00:04:17.120 --> 00:04:19.520
 Then we grab the X register.

00:04:19.520 --> 00:04:21.360
 Make sure it's a number, not a string.

00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:24.080
 That's probably just conservative programming.

00:04:24.080 --> 00:04:27.440
 Then we take the base address plus the X value.

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:31.520
 That's our offsetting to our index by X.

00:04:31.520 --> 00:04:36.960
 And then we go grab the real memory, CPU.memory of the effective address.

00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:38.080
 What is memory?

00:04:38.080 --> 00:04:41.520
 Here's a 256-byte array.

00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:44.640
 And then we set the accumulator to whatever came out of that memory.

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:48.640
 And we update the status flags and we set the P increment to 2.

00:04:48.640 --> 00:04:53.360
 So again, this is about 1300 lines of code.

00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:55.760
 I would not claim it's a perfect emulator.

00:04:55.760 --> 00:05:01.200
 I just did it well enough to make it so that you can learn what you need to learn in this class.

00:05:01.200 --> 00:05:06.880
 I would say probably I could make it a lot more accurate if I made it

00:05:07.440 --> 00:05:09.120
 2500 lines of code.

00:05:09.120 --> 00:05:12.400
 If I did things like made all the memory mapping for sound and stuff work,

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:16.400
 it'd probably be three or four times larger, maybe 5000 lines of code.

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:18.640
 That's not a lot of code.

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:22.480
 The interesting thing is that most modern processors on phones and computers

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:26.400
 are so fast that even if we're writing something in JavaScript

00:05:26.400 --> 00:05:28.800
 that's emulating historical machine code,

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:31.920
 it can do that far faster than the original hardware.

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:37.040
 So if you build an emulator for a 6502 and you want to do 1 MHz,

00:05:37.040 --> 00:05:39.680
 well, you probably will have to slow it down.

00:05:39.680 --> 00:05:44.640
 And things like graphics are way better in modern environments

00:05:44.640 --> 00:05:46.880
 and they don't take a lot of resources.

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:50.880
 So if we go back to the 70s and the 80s,

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:55.760
 people would buy things like Atari 2600s and play them on their televisions.

00:05:55.760 --> 00:05:59.840
 They would have these plug-in ROM modules that had the code in it.

00:05:59.840 --> 00:06:00.880
 That's the machine code.

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:04.240
 And so there's an effort to capture these

00:06:04.240 --> 00:06:07.360
 and you can actually disassemble these.

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:10.720
 ROMs are things you can read with ROM readers

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:12.800
 and then you can extract the machine code

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:15.280
 and then you can build an emulator

00:06:15.280 --> 00:06:21.280
 and it turns out that the Atari 2600 has a 6502 in it.

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:24.720
 So the console that you plugged into the Atari 2600,

00:06:24.720 --> 00:06:28.560
 that machine code is 6502 machine code.

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:33.280
 So you build an emulator including all the graphics capabilities of the 2600

00:06:33.280 --> 00:06:39.280
 and so you can emulate a game like Space Invaders on the Atari 2600

00:06:39.280 --> 00:06:41.920
 in your browsers and completely play it.

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:44.160
 I encourage you to go ahead and play it.

00:06:44.160 --> 00:06:48.080
 If you slow down the startup,

00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:49.680
 once things get cached in your browsers,

00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:52.080
 this screen goes by so fast you won't even see it.

00:06:52.080 --> 00:06:53.520
 I had to record it to catch it.

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:57.440
 You can see what's going on as the game is being loaded.

00:06:57.440 --> 00:06:59.360
 It's looking at the files,

00:06:59.360 --> 00:07:02.800
 it's the machine code for the game

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:05.200
 and it's running it in the browser

00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:08.640
 using a piece of software written in WASM.

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:11.680
 Now it's not written in JavaScript, it's written in WASM.

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:13.280
 What is WASM?

00:07:13.280 --> 00:07:15.120
 WASM is Web Assembly.

00:07:15.120 --> 00:07:20.560
 So I built a machine language emulator in JavaScript that you were using

00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:24.160
 but there is a low-level high-performance machine language emulator

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:25.680
 built into web browsers,

00:07:25.680 --> 00:07:29.360
 recent web browsers called Web Assembly.

00:07:29.360 --> 00:07:31.280
 So Web Assembly is a machine code

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:33.920
 that is not intended to be built in hardware

00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:37.680
 but intended to be emulated very, very rapidly by hardware.

00:07:37.680 --> 00:07:40.480
 So for a wide range of software,

00:07:40.480 --> 00:07:44.000
 you can do surprisingly complex things

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.160
 and then compile them to WASM,

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:47.920
 download them into a browser

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:50.640
 and run them in a browser

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:52.320
 with a little JavaScript library

00:07:52.320 --> 00:07:55.760
 that provides things like file opening, et cetera, et cetera.

00:07:55.760 --> 00:07:57.600
 Now I want to show you a bit of WASM.

00:07:57.600 --> 00:08:01.120
 It's got a little bit different syntax than most assembly languages

00:08:01.120 --> 00:08:04.240
 but it still is a very succinct

00:08:04.240 --> 00:08:07.040
 one-to-one correspondence to binary machine code.

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:09.920
 I will also show you in the C Programming for Everybody course

00:08:09.920 --> 00:08:12.880
 that I teach at www.ccfree.com,

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:16.000
 the C Playground actually doesn't run the code in the server.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.480
 It compiles C to WASM in the server

00:08:18.480 --> 00:08:21.040
 and then runs WASM in the user's browser.

00:08:21.040 --> 00:08:25.520
 So you can't run an infinite loop in my C Programming for Everybody course

00:08:25.520 --> 00:08:27.120
 and break my server.

00:08:27.120 --> 00:08:29.840
 You can write an infinite loop and break your browser

00:08:29.840 --> 00:08:32.240
 but that is your browser.

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:35.200
 So let's take a little bit of a look at WebAssembly.

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:36.640
 WASM is a little bit different.

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:38.560
 So you don't see, for example, an accumulator.

00:08:38.560 --> 00:08:41.920
 It actually has a stack and it has operands on the stack

00:08:41.920 --> 00:08:43.920
 and you put operands on the stack

00:08:43.920 --> 00:08:45.680
 and then you operate on the operands of the stack

00:08:45.680 --> 00:08:47.440
 and then replace things on the stack.

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:49.280
 It's a very simple execution model

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:51.680
 but it's still very, very low level.

00:08:51.680 --> 00:08:55.120
 And what this is, is this is printing Hello World.

00:08:55.120 --> 00:08:57.200
 You see this sort of indentation.

00:08:58.080 --> 00:08:59.920
 It still is machine code. If you look below,

00:08:59.920 --> 00:09:03.440
 there's about 90 bytes of machine code that I dumped

00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:07.120
 from this particular bit of code compiled into WASM.

00:09:07.120 --> 00:09:09.200
 It uses a little different syntax

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:13.040
 because it really doesn't want to expose labels in WASM.

00:09:13.040 --> 00:09:15.120
 It really wants there to be a stack.

00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:18.080
 It wants to be a set of nested modules

00:09:18.080 --> 00:09:20.000
 and variable scopes and things like that.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:25.040
 But still it's an assembly language and it is got nesting.

00:09:25.040 --> 00:09:28.480
 So you tend not to use labels in the same way

00:09:28.480 --> 00:09:31.200
 that we use labels in more traditional assembly language

00:09:31.200 --> 00:09:33.120
 and machine language.

00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:35.680
 And here is a simple example of a thing.

00:09:35.680 --> 00:09:38.320
 You can just go to this website and play with it.

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:42.160
 You can write C code, you hit the run code button.

00:09:42.160 --> 00:09:44.480
 It uploads the C code to a server,

00:09:44.480 --> 00:09:46.480
 which then compiles it to WASM.

00:09:46.480 --> 00:09:49.600
 That takes very little time and it downloads that WASM

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:54.160
 and then it runs that WASM as output and shows the output of it.

00:09:54.160 --> 00:09:58.320
 That also means that in that WASM compiler for C,

00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:00.400
 there's a whole standard library,

00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:02.800
 includes stdio.h and the printf.

00:10:02.800 --> 00:10:04.800
 That's been compiled to WASM as well.

00:10:04.800 --> 00:10:07.040
 So the WASM you get back from Inscriptum

00:10:07.040 --> 00:10:11.120
 is much larger than just a pure WASM bit of code

00:10:11.120 --> 00:10:14.080
 because it's compiled the C library as well

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:16.720
 so that you can do things like printf and scanf

00:10:16.720 --> 00:10:21.200
 and other kinds of things that you would do in a C application.

00:10:22.720 --> 00:10:29.600
 So emulators going forward are so fast and becoming ubiquitous

00:10:29.600 --> 00:10:32.480
 that it's kind of foolish to write native code

00:10:32.480 --> 00:10:36.320
 for certain things like video games and other things.

00:10:36.320 --> 00:10:39.440
 And so the fact that you're playing with an emulator

00:10:39.440 --> 00:10:41.680
 going forward in the future,

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:45.680
 you may be writing code for production that runs in an emulator.

00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:55.640
 (jazz piano music)

